=========================================
🔥 MOST ASKED C++ INTERVIEW Q&A (CORE SHEET)
=========================================

========================
1. BASIC C++ (1–10)
========================

1. What is C++?
A: A general-purpose, object-oriented programming language.

2. Why C++ is used?
A: Fast, close to hardware, supports OOP + low-level memory control.

3. What are OOP principles?
A: Encapsulation, Abstraction, Inheritance, Polymorphism.

4. Difference between C and C++?
A: C = procedural, C++ = object-oriented + STL.

5. What is class?
A: Blueprint of an object.

6. What is object?
A: Instance of a class.

7. What is constructor?
A: Initializes object automatically.

8. What is destructor?
A: Cleans up object memory automatically.

9. Can constructor be overloaded?
A: Yes.

10. Can destructor be overloaded?
A: No.

-----------------------------------------

========================
2. MEMORY MANAGEMENT (11–20)
========================

11. Stack vs Heap?
A: Stack = automatic, fast. Heap = manual, dynamic.

12. new vs malloc?
A: new calls constructor, malloc does not.

13. delete vs free?
A: delete calls destructor, free does not.

14. What is memory leak?
A: Memory not freed after use.

15. What is dangling pointer?
A: Pointer pointing to deleted memory.

16. What is RAII?
A: Resource tied to object lifetime.

17. What is shallow copy?
A: Copies pointer only.

18. What is deep copy?
A: Copies actual data.

19. Why use heap memory?
A: For dynamic lifetime control.

20. What is fragmentation?
A: Wasted memory gaps.

-----------------------------------------

========================
3. POINTERS (21–30)
========================

21. What is pointer?
A: Stores address of variable.

22. What is reference?
A: Alias of variable.

23. Pointer vs reference?
A: Pointer can be null, reference cannot.

24. What is null pointer?
A: Pointer pointing to nothing.

25. What is wild pointer?
A: Uninitialized pointer.

26. What is dangling pointer?
A: Points to freed memory.

27. const pointer?
A: Pointer cannot change address.

28. pointer to const?
A: Value cannot change.

29. Can pointer be reassigned?
A: Yes.

30. Can reference be reassigned?
A: No.

-----------------------------------------

========================
4. OOP CONCEPTS (31–45)
========================

31. What is encapsulation?
A: Data hiding using classes.

32. What is abstraction?
A: Hide implementation details.

33. What is inheritance?
A: One class acquires properties of another.

34. What is polymorphism?
A: Same function, different behavior.

35. What is virtual function?
A: Runtime polymorphism.

36. What is pure virtual function?
A: Function with no body.

37. What is abstract class?
A: Class with at least one pure virtual function.

38. What is object slicing?
A: Derived data lost when copied to base object.

39. What is friend function?
A: Access private members of class.

40. What is static keyword?
A: Shared across all objects.

41. What is this pointer?
A: Points to current object.

42. Can constructor be virtual?
A: No.

43. Can destructor be virtual?
A: Yes.

44. What is override keyword?
A: Ensures correct overriding.

45. What is final keyword?
A: Prevent inheritance or override.

-----------------------------------------

========================
5. MODERN C++ (46–60)
========================

46. What is nullptr?
A: Type-safe null pointer.

47. What is auto?
A: Automatic type deduction.

48. What is lambda?
A: Anonymous function.

49. What is move semantics?
A: Transfers ownership instead of copying.

50. What is std::move?
A: Converts object to rvalue.

51. What is rvalue?
A: Temporary object.

52. What is lvalue?
A: Object with memory address.

53. What is constexpr?
A: Compile-time evaluation.

54. What is enum class?
A: Scoped enum.

55. What is initializer list?
A: Uniform initialization method.

56. What is noexcept?
A: No exception guarantee.

57. What is variadic template?
A: Template with variable arguments.

58. What is perfect forwarding?
A: Preserve value category.

59. What is delete keyword?
A: Disable function.

60. What is default keyword?
A: Ask compiler to generate function.

-----------------------------------------

========================
6. STL BASICS (61–75)
========================

61. What is STL?
A: Standard Template Library.

62. Components of STL?
A: Containers, Algorithms, Iterators.

63. What is vector?
A: Dynamic array.

64. What is deque?
A: Double-ended queue.

65. What is list?
A: Doubly linked list.

66. What is stack?
A: LIFO container adaptor.

67. What is queue?
A: FIFO container adaptor.

68. What is priority_queue?
A: Heap-based structure.

69. What is set?
A: Sorted unique elements.

70. What is map?
A: Key-value sorted structure.

71. What is unordered_map?
A: Hash table.

72. What is iterator?
A: Pointer-like object.

73. What is begin()?
A: First element.

74. What is end()?
A: Past-the-end element.

75. What is STL advantage?
A: Reusable + efficient + generic.

-----------------------------------------

========================
7. STL + COMPLEXITY (76–90)
========================

76. vector access complexity?
A: O(1)

77. map access complexity?
A: O(log n)

78. unordered_map complexity?
A: O(1) average

79. set complexity?
A: O(log n)

80. priority_queue push?
A: O(log n)

81. stack push/pop?
A: O(1)

82. queue push/pop?
A: O(1)

83. vector reallocation?
A: Happens when capacity full.

84. Why deque used in STL?
A: Efficient front + back operations.

85. Why map uses Red-Black Tree?
A: Keeps data sorted + balanced.

86. Why unordered_map is fast?
A: Hashing.

87. Why vector faster than list?
A: Cache locality.

88. Why list is slower?
A: Pointer-based traversal.

89. Why stack has no iteration?
A: Enforces LIFO.

90. Why queue has no iteration?
A: Enforces FIFO.

-----------------------------------------

========================
8. FINAL INTERVIEW FAVORITES (91–100)
========================

91. What is RAII?
A: Resource tied to object lifetime.

92. What is memory leak?
A: Unreleased memory.

93. What is dangling pointer?
A: Invalid memory reference.

94. Difference map vs unordered_map?
A: Tree vs Hash table.

95. Why virtual destructor?
A: Prevent memory leak in polymorphism.

96. What is slicing?
A: Loss of derived data.

97. Why STL used?
A: Faster development + optimized code.

98. What is iterator invalidation?
A: Iterator becomes invalid after modification.

99. What is move semantics benefit?
A: Avoid unnecessary copying.

100. Why C++ is fast?
A: Close to hardware + no GC + manual control.

